# 3.
(ggplot(df1, 
        aes(x='income', 
            y='life_exp', 
            size='population', 
            fill='four_regions')) +
    geom_point() +
    
    scale_x_log10(
        # Adds the breaks 
        breaks=[1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000], 
        limits = (500,64000),
        # Labels each break
        labels=['1000', '2000', '4000', '8000', '16k', '32k', '64k']) + 
    
    scale_y_continuous(
        # Adds limits to values between 15 and 90
        limits = (15,90),
        # Breaks y axis from 20 to 90 every 10
        breaks=range(20, 91, 10)) + 

    scale_size(range = (2,30)) +
    
    theme_minimal() + 
    labs(x='Income',
         y='Life expectancy',
         fill = 'World Regions') +
    
    scale_fill_manual(values=region_colors)+
    
    annotate('text', x=4000, y=40, label='2010', size=200, alpha=0.4, color='gray') +
    annotate('text', x=5000, y=90, label='Income Level 1        *        Level 2        *        Level 3            *        Level 4', size=20, alpha=0.5, color='Black') +
    annotate('text', x=500, y=90, label='years', size=10, alpha=0.4, color='black', angle=90) +

    guides(size=False) +

    theme(
        figure_size=(14,6)
    )
)

(ggplot(df2, 
        aes(x='exports', 
            y='imports', 
            size='energy', 
            fill='four_regions')) +
    geom_point() +
    
    scale_x_continuous(

    labs(x='Export (% of GDP)',
         y='Imports (% of GDP)',
         fill = 'World Regions') +
    
    scale_fill_manual(values=region_colors)+
    
    annotate('text', x=90, y=200, label='1997', size=200, alpha=0.4, color='gray') +

    theme(
        figure_size=(14,6)
    )
)

geom_line is not a good geometric for displaying exports and imports because it implies an ordered relationship between points, which doesnât exist in this context. Since exports and imports are independent continuous variables without an sequential order, using a line can mislead by suggesting false connections or trends between them. A scatter plot or density plot is more appropriate for visualizing their relationship.

         fill = 'World Regions') +
    
    scale_fill_manual(values=region_colors)+
    
    annotate('text', x=50, y=4000, label='2001', size=200, alpha=0.4, color='gray') +

    theme(
        figure_size=(14,6)
    )
)
/Users/Steven/Documents/Documents - MacBook Pro/Cal Poly/MSBA/Fall 2024/GSB-544/Labs/Lab-1/.venv/lib/python3.12/site-packages/plotnine/layer.py:364: PlotnineWarning: geom_point : Removed 32 rows containing missing values.

/Library/Frameworks/Python.framework/Versions/3.12/lib/python3.12/pprint.py:629: FutureWarning: Using repr(plot) to draw and show the plot figure is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use plot.show().

A 2D density plot is good geometric for visualizing the relationship between internet_users and GDP because it displays areas where these variables have high or low concentrations. We can see where each World Regions peaks in internet_users and GDP and it helps identify patterns in their relationship. It is very similar to the scatter plot but removes individual points.
